In [4]:
features = ['bill_length_mm','bill_depth_mm','flipper_length_mm', 'body_mass_g']
km = KMeans(n_clusters=2, random_state=42).fit(penguins[features])
In [5]:
penguins['cluster'] = km.predict(penguins[features])

contingency_table = penguins.groupby(['species','cluster']).size().unstack('cluster', fill_value=0)
contingency_table

species
Adelie 138 14

It looks like the Adelie and Chinstrap species very often end up in the same clusters. The Gentoo species seems to be consistantly decently separeted from the other two species. When two species are roughly in the cluster, it means that there aren't too many statistically significant differences between the two species.
